This is a very Galkovsky style Wikipedia article. Unexplained imperial decline with lack of historical continuity. Missing first hand textual evidence and just speculation based on very few known but vaguely understood events. Dubious climate change called in to fill missing gaps

It's literally called "the Cambodian dark ages" so it's almost on the nose. Resolves around the 17th century with printing making it impossible to censor published text. The primary Galkovsky idea is any time "ecological catastrophe" appears it means no one knows what happened.

Reading about the Montauk Project book and realized that Deadpool capeshit movie was probably partially based on it, the idea of people being physically tortured until they unlock their secret psychic "superpowers" of remote vision, violence, etc., they 100% got it from there imo

I think it's the same thing which Julius Evola described as how in some extreme cases of pain and torture a person's soul can exit out of the heart and leave the body, sensing no pain there. Varg Vikernes said this happened to him during a childhood high altitude skiing accident.

I've run into Peter Moon the co-author of the Montauk book before online, related to some Miguel Serrano type circles, including that Twin Peaks analysis. David Lynch himself might have taken the idea of "monstrous creature coming out of man-made portal" out of Montauk Project.

Also at least someone at Valve is into Montauk or at least the Philadelphia Experiment. But it's crazy to think the same few conspiracy theories and people are basically behind Half-Life, Twin Peaks, Stranger Things (originally called Montauk) and it's all about Nazis and stuff

We still have a lot of jokes about the Chukchi here in Bulgaria, usually paired with a geologist. I will translate one for you

Russian joke: A Chukcha and a geologist are walking by the snowy Chukotska Sea coast talking when they see a large polar bear coming at them. The Chukcha immediately starts putting on his ski. "It's useless" says the geologist with resignation. "We can never outrun a polar bear."
The Chukcha finishes putting on his ski, thinks a bit, and responds. "Chukcha does not need outrun bear. Chukcha only needs outrun you." And slides off away from the geologist with the ski.
